Dev+Biol%22%5Bjour%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n-   [Search in NLM Catalog](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nlmcatalog?term=%22Semin+Cell+Dev+Biol%22%5BTitle+Abbreviation%5D)\n-   [Add to Search](#)\n\n. 2012 Sep;23(7):794-802.\n\ndoi: 10.1016/j.semcdb.2012.04.001. Epub 2012 Apr 15.\n\n# Hippo signalling in the G2/M cell cycle phase: lessons learned from the yeast MEN and SIN pathways\n\n[Alexander Hergovich](/?term=Hergovich+A&cauthor_id=22525225)  [1](#full-view-affiliation-1 \"UCL Cancer Institute, University College London, London, United Kingdom. a.hergovich@ucl.ac.uk\") , [Brian A Hemmings](/?term=Hemmings+BA&cauthor_id=22525225)\n\nAffiliations Expand\n\n### Affiliation\n\n-   1 UCL Cancer Institute, University College London, London, United Kingdom. a.hergovich@ucl.ac.uk\n\n-   PMID: **22525225**\n-   PMCID: [PMC3459816](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3459816/)\n-   DOI: [10.1016/j.semcdb.2012.04.001](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.semcdb.2012.04.001)\n\nItem in Clipboard\n\nReview\n\n# Hippo signalling in the G2/M cell cycle phase: lessons learned from the yeast MEN and SIN pathways\n\nAlexander Hergovich et al. Semin Cell Dev Biol. 2012 Sep.\n\nShow details\n\nDisplay options\n\nDisplay options\n\nFormat Abstract PubMed PMID\n\nSemin Cell Dev Biol\n\nActions\n\n-   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22Semin+Cell+Dev+Biol%22%5Bjour%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n-   [Search in NLM Catalog](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nlmcatalog?term=%22Semin+Cell+Dev+Biol%22%5BTitle+Abbreviation%5D)\n-   [Add to Search](#)\n\n. 2012 Sep;23(7):794-802.\n\ndoi: 10.1016/j.semcdb.2012.04.001. Epub 2012 Apr 15.\n\n### Authors\n\n[Alexander Hergovich](/?term=Hergovich+A&cauthor_id=22525225)  [1](#short-view-affiliation-1 \"UCL Cancer Institute, University College London, London, United Kingdom. a.hergovich@ucl.ac.uk\") , [Brian A Hemmings](/?term=Hemmings+BA&cauthor_id=22525225)\n\n### Affiliation\n\n-   1 UCL Cancer Institute, University College London, London, United Kingdom. a.hergovich@ucl.ac.uk\n\n-   PMID: **22525225**\n-   PMCID: [PMC3459816](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3459816/)\n-   DOI: [10.1016/j.semcdb.2012.04.001](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.semcdb.2012.04.001)\n\nItem in Clipboard\n\nFull text links Cite\n\nDisplay options\n\nDisplay options\n\nFormat AbstractPubMedPMID\n\n## Abstract\n\nOver the past decade Hippo kinase signalling has been established as an essential tumour suppressor pathway controlling tissue growth in flies and mammals. All members of the Hippo core signalling cassette are conserved from yeast to humans, whereby the yeast analogues of Hippo, Mats and Lats are central components of the mitotic exit network and septation initiation network in budding and fission yeast, respectively. Here, we discuss how far core Hippo signalling components in Drosophila melanogaster and mammals have reported similar mitotic functions as already established for their highly conserved yeast counterparts.\n\nCopyright © 2012. Published by Elsevier Ltd.\n\n[PubMed Disclaimer](/disclaimer/)\n\n## Figures\n\n [![Figure 1](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/563c/3459816/0fff1e4acd23/ukmss-49049-f0001.gif)](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/563c/3459816/0b7f03bb718f/ukmss-49049-f0001.jpg) \n\n**\n\nFigure 1. The MEN and SIN in…\n\n**\n\n**\n\nFigure 1. The MEN and SIN in yeast\n\n**\n\nIn budding and fission yeast, MEN and…\n\n**Figure 1. The MEN and SIN in yeast**\n\nIn budding and fission yeast, MEN and SIN core signalling encompasses members of five conserved protein groups. Scaffolding proteins (brown) assist Ste20-like kinases (yellow) in their activation of LATS/NDR kinases (green) in complex with a MOB protein (red). This kinase/co-activator complex then phosphorylates and thereby activates a Cdc14 phosphatase (blue), which finally results in CDK1 inhibition and subsequent exit from mitosis and cytokinesis. Please note that the indicated SIN-phosphorylation of Mob1p is predicted by the conservation between MEN and SIN signalling and not based on scientific evidence. Phosphorylations are indicated by “P” in blue.\n\n [![Figure 2](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/563c/3459816/37287fd023ee/ukmss-49049-f0002.gif)](https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/563c/3459816/9aded9bfe54e/ukmss-49049-f0002.jpg) \n\n**\n\nFigure 2. Comparison of MEN and Hippo…\n\n**\n\n**\n\nFigure 2. Comparison of MEN and Hippo signalling components in mitotic exit and cytokinesis\n\n**\n\n*S.…*\n\n**Figure 2. Comparison of MEN and Hippo signalling components in mitotic exit and cytokinesis**\n\n*S. cerevisiae, D. melanogaster* and mammals utilise a highly conserved signalling module composed of scaffolding proteins (brown), Ste20-like kinases (yellow), LATS/NDR kinases (green), MOB proteins (red), and possibly Cdc14 phosphatases (blue). While this signalling cassette is essential for mitotic exit in yeast, the mitotic role of Hippo signalling is debateable. Currently, we do not know whether Hippo signalling as illustrated here is playing any role in mitotic exit and cytokinesis. Nevertheless, some factors (RASSF1A, LATS1/2 and Cdc14) have been reported to play a role in mitotic exit and cytokinesis. Otherwise, question marks highlight proteins that so far have no reported role in mitotic exit and/or cytokinesis. Phosphorylations are indicated by “P” in blue.\n\n[See this image and copyright information in PMC](#)\n\n## References\n\n1.  1.  Hanahan D, Weinberg RA. Hallmarks of cancer: the next generation. Cell. 2011;144:646–674. - [PubMed](/21376230/)\n2.  1.  Fang X, Zhang P. Aneuploidy and tumorigenesis. Semin Cell Dev Biol. 2011;22:595–601. - [PMC](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3651908/) - [PubMed](/21392584/)\n3.  1.  Holland AJ, Cleveland DW. Boveri revisited: chromosomal instability, aneuploidy and tumorigenesis. Nat Rev Mol Cell Biol. 2009;10:478–487. - [PMC](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3154738/) - [PubMed](/19546858/)\n4.  1.  Walczak CE, Cai S, Khodjakov A. Mechanisms of chromosome behaviour during mitosis. Nat Rev Mol Cell Biol. 2010;11:91–102. - [PMC](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2893392/) - [PubMed](/20068571/)\n5.  1.  Hochegger H, Takeda S, Hunt T. Cyclin-dependent kinases and cell-cycle transitions: does one fit all? Nat Rev Mol Cell Biol. 2008;9:910–916. - [PubMed](/18813291/)\n\nShow all 121 references\n\n## Publication types\n\n-   Research Support, Non-U.S. Gov't\n    \n    Actions\n    \n    -   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22Research+Support%2C+Non-U.S.+Gov%27t%22%5Bpt%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n    -   [Search in MeSH](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh?term=Research+Support%2C+Non-U.S.+Gov%27t)\n    -   [Add to Search](#)\n    \n-   Review\n    \n    Actions\n    \n    -   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22Review%22%5Bpt%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n    -   [Search in MeSH](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh?term=Review)\n    -   [Add to Search](#)\n    \n\n## MeSH terms\n\n-   Animals\n    \n    Actions\n    \n    -   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22Animals%22%5BMeSH%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n    -   [Search in MeSH](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh?term=Animals)\n    -   [Add to Search](#)\n    \n-   Cell Division\\*\n    \n    Actions\n    \n    -   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22Cell+Division%22%5BMAJR%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n    -   [Search in MeSH](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh?term=Cell+Division)\n    -   [Add to Search](#)\n    \n-   G2 Phase\\*\n    \n    Actions\n    \n    -   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22G2+Phase%22%5BMAJR%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n    -   [Search in MeSH](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh?term=G2+Phase)\n    -   [Add to Search](#)\n    \n-   Humans\n    \n    Actions\n    \n    -   [Search in PubMed](/?term=%22Humans%22%5BMeSH%5D&sort=date&sort_order=desc)\n    -   [Search in MeSH](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/mesh?term=Humans)\n    -   [Add to Search](#)\n    \n-   Protein Serine-Threonine Kinases / metabolism\n    \n    Actions\n    \n    -   [Search in